<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910412-0040</DOCNO><DOCID>910412-0040.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Puritan-Bennett Corp.:   First-Quarter Net Plunged   Due to a Halt in Shipments</HL><DATE>04/12/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   PBEN</CO><MS>CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>MEDICAL SUPPLIES, EYEGLASS MANUFACTURERS (MDS)</IN><NS>EARNINGS (ERN)</NS><RE>KANSAS (KS)</RE><LP>   Puritan-Bennett Corp., Overland Park, Kan., saidfirst-quarter net income was cut by nearly two-thirds toabout 10 cents a share mainly because of a halt last month inshipments of faulty ventilators produced by the pulmonaryequipment maker.   Prior to discovering the &quot;relatively minor technicalcondition&quot; that triggered the delay in shipping its 7200series ventilators, Puritan-Bennett estimated earnings of 25cents to 30 cents a share. A year earlier, net was $4.2million, or 37 cents a share.</LP><TEXT>   The company also said that about three cents a share ofthe charge in the first quarter is a result offoreign-currency translation losses due to the strengtheningdollar. The company expects to release final results nextweek.   Burton A. Dole, chairman and president, said &quot;actionnecessary to correct the {ventilator} condition is now in theprocess of being implemented.&quot; He said the company expects toship all of the ventilators held up by the problem in thesecond quarter.</TEXT></DOC>